properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow becoming heavy tonight. This Snowfall Warning replaces a Winter Weather Travel Advisory that was previously in effect. Locally heavy snowfall amounts of 15 cm within 12 hour is now expected tonight. Snow has begun and will become heavy tonight. It will continue through Friday before tapering to flurries Friday night. Total snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 cm is expected. Strong northwesterly winds gusting up to 50 km/h will develop on Friday resulting in localized areas of blowing snow. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Upwards of 20 cm of snow is expected by Friday morning. A Pacific frontal system moving into the region is forecast to bring more snow to southern British Columbia. Snow is expected to intensify tonight for the Coquihalla Highway - Hope to Merritt and Highway 3 - Hope to Princeton via Allison Pass sections and taper off to periods of light snow Friday morning. Another significant system will approach the region Friday night with additional amounts of 15 to 20 cm possible for Saturday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls likely beginning Friday afternoon through Saturday morning. Locally heavy snow squalls are forecast to develop to the northeast of Georgian Bay as cold southwesterly winds develop Friday afternoon into Friday night. Locally heavy snowfall accumulations in excess of 10 cm will be possible with these snow squalls, particularly Friday night into Saturday morning. Given the strong southwesterly winds gusting up to 60 km/h, areas of low visibility in heavy snow and blowing snow will be a concern. Motorists should consider changing travel plans accordingly. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard and/or near-blizzard conditions are expected to begin Friday and persist for most of the weekend. A trough of low pressure over Hudson Bay along with a ridge of high pressure over NWT will produce strong winds over the southern Kivalliq beginning Friday. Northwesterly gusts to 70 km/h combined with light snow will combine to produce blowing snow starting Friday afternoon or Friday evening in Arviat and Rankin Inlet. Conditions will worsen on Saturday with blizzard conditions expected to remain until Monday morning. Uncertainty still exists regarding the onset of these blizzards. This watch could be upgraded to a blizzard warning in these regions or expanded to other regions as necessary. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for midnight to early Friday morning. Snow is expected to move into the area from the west just after midnight and continue until early Friday morning. At any location, the heaviest snowfall is most likely for the first two or three hours after onset. Snow may briefly become mixed with rain overnight along the shoreline of Lake Ontario. Total snowfall amounts by early Friday morning will range from 2 to 5 cm near Lake Ontario and 5 to 10 cm further inland. Road conditions are expected to rapidly deteriorate once the snow arrives. Untreated roads may suddenly become snow covered and slippery. Motorists should allow for extra time to reach their destination. The first part of the Friday morning commute may be affected, especially in areas where precipitation falls as all snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. An arctic ridge of high pressure will allow skies to remain relatively clear tonight. This ridge will also allow for a very cold air mass from the north to sink over portions of southern and central Saskatchewan starting tonight. Along with winds of 10 to 20 km/h, extreme wind chill values of -40 or colder will occur tonight into Friday. Many areas rebound only slightly from these bitterly cold values during the day on Friday before another round of more expansive cold sets in across the province Friday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow becoming heavy this evening into tonight. Snow has begun and will increase in intensity this evening into tonight. The snow will ease in intensity Friday morning before ending later in the day. Total snowfall amounts of 20 to 30 cm are likely by the time the snow comes to an end. Travel conditions along Highway 17 between Nipigon and Wawa will likely become hazardous due to accumulating snow and very low visibility. Motorists should consider changing travel plans accordingly. The town of Wawa is expected to receive lesser amounts than areas farther west along the shore of Lake Superior. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. A ridge of arctic high pressure will keep skies relatively clear and allow for a very cold air mass to move into portions of northern Manitoba from Nunavut tonight. Along with winds of 10 to 15 km/h, extreme cold wind chills of -45 or colder are expected over the next few days as the stagnant area of high pressure remains parked over the province. Extreme cold warnings will likely be expanded to include most of the province come Friday night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Sant at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
